1 C. 1. If a notary public willfully and intentionally violates
2 the provisions of this section, then that notary public shall be
3 guilty of a misdemeanor and subject to a fine of up to Five Hundred
4 Dollars ($500.00).
5 2. A notary public shall be authorized to notarize a maximum of
6 twenty absentee ballot affidavits for a single election, except as
7 provided in paragraphs 2 3 and 3 4 of this subsection.
8 2. 3. A notary public may be authorized to notarize more than
9 twenty absentee ballot affidavits at a single election with the
10 written approval of the secretary of the county election board.
11 Such approval shall apply for affidavits notarized within the county
12 served by the county election board secretary.
13 3. 4. The limitation required by this subsection shall not
14 apply to the notarizing of absentee ballot affidavits at the place
15 of business of a notary public that is open to the general public
16 during the normal business hours of the notary public.
17 D. 1. If more than ten absentee ballots for a single election
18 are requested to be mailed to a single mailing address, the
19 secretary of the county election board shall immediately notify the
20 district attorney for that county and the Secretary of the State
21 Election Board.
22 2. Upon receipt of such notification, the district attorney, or
23 a member of law enforcement designated by the district attorney,
24
